A Language Model (LM) in AI is a system that learns patterns in human language and predicts the next word (or token) in a sequence. It helps computers understand, generate, summarize, translate, and answer questions using natural language.
Simple Example
If you type:
	"I love to drink"
A language model predicts the most likely next word, such as:
	"coffee", "tea", or "water"
It learns these patterns by training on massive amounts of text data.
→ We trained the large amount of data by using google information Wikipedia information to that model, so it will generates the new data content using existing data. 
						             Types of Language Models
1. Statistical Language Models
2. Neural Language Models
3. Transformer-Based Language Models
   
1. Statistical Language Models: SLM also called small language model , specific amount of data is trained 
→7 to 10 million parameters 

"A Statistical Language Model predicts the probability of a word or sentence using statistical information collected from a large text corpus."
SLM calculates the probability of each word based on training data and chooses the most probable one.
Example:

P(tea) = 0.45
P(coffee) = 0.40
P(water) = 0.10
P(laptop) = 0.0001
Prediction:
O/P:
I drink a cup of tea  

Examples
	• Unigram Model =0 words
	• Bigram Model =1 previous word
	• Trigram Model =2 previous words
	• N-gram Model =3 previous words

