Feed Forward Neural Network(FFNN):  it only looks at a fixed window and cannot remember the entire sentence.
Because information only moves forward: A Feed Forward Neural Network (FFNN) is the simplest type of Artificial Neural Network where information moves in one direction only( it only see the particular word and predict and then  generate the future token, a sentence cannot see the entire sentence )

Input
 ↓
Hidden Layer
 ↓
Output
FFNN = Fixed Context + No Memory + Forward-Only Processing. 

Recurrent neural Network(RNN): RNN can remember previous information using its hidden state.
RNN = Has Memory
which allows them to remember information from previous inputs and use it while processing the current input.
Better context understanding than FFNN.

It create future token(hidden) by understanding the previous token 
	
Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM):Designed to remember information for a long period of time.
Why LSTM Was Introduced
Problem with RNN
RNN can remember recent information, but as sequences become longer, it gradually forgets older information.
→ So that’s why we introduced the LSTM has more memory cell to store the data and understand the context of the sentence
→ An LSTM is an improved version of RNN that can learn and remember long-term dependencies in sequential data using a memory cell and three gates: Forget Gate, Input Gate, and Output Gate.

This is called the Vanishing Gradient Problem, which means that as information passes through many steps in an RNN, the learning signal (gradient) becomes very small. As a result, the network gradually forgets important information from earlier parts of a long sequence and struggles to learn long-term dependencies, making it difficult to remember context from far back in the input.
LSTM was introduced to solve this problem by maintaining a dedicated memory cell.

Architecture of LSTM
Input
  ↓
Forget Gate
  ↓
Input Gate
  ↓
Memory Cell
  ↓
Output Gate
  ↓
Output

Gated Recurrent Unit (GRU): A GRU is a simplified version of LSTM that uses fewer gates and parameters to remember important information over long sequences while training faster.
While compare to the lstm it was trained so fastly. 
Researchers wanted a model that could:
✅ Remember long-term information
✅ Solve vanishing gradient problem
✅ Train faster
✅ Use fewer parameters
This led to the development of GRU.
This is exactly how GRU works:
	• Reset Gate → removes irrelevant information.
	• Update Gate → keeps useful information and adds new information.




